==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|aberrātus}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|aberrō||wander, stray or deviate from}}, formed from {{m|la|ab||from, away from}} + {{m|la|errō||stray}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.ə.ɹeɪt/|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|aberrat}}

# {{lbl|en|intransitive}} To go [[astray]]; to [[diverge]]; to [[deviate]] (from); deviate from. {{defdate|mid 18the century}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=4}}</ref>
#* {{quote-book|author=De Quincey|passage=Their own defective and '''aberrating''' vision.}}
# {{lbl|en|transitive}} To [[distort]]; to cause [[aberration]] of. {{defdate|late 19th century}}<ref name=SOED/>

====Usage notes====
* The transitive sense is chiefly used in the past tense (as ''[[aberrated]]'').

